Looking at your Application class header, you are currently defining a very rigid architecture where every "manager" is a std::unique_ptr owned directly by the Application class.

Since you mentioned these need to be a "reactive layer," you should move away from raw unique_ptr members for every single system. Instead, consider a System Registry or Service Locator pattern. This allows your systems to interact with each other without the Application class having to know about every single one.

Given your voxel engine focus and current architecture, here are the managers you should add to handle that "reactive" requirement:
1. The Essential Reactive Managers

    Event Manager (Message Bus): This is the heart of a "reactive" engine. Instead of the Renderer calling the AssetManager directly, you broadcast an event (e.g., Event::AssetLoaded). Other systems subscribe to these events.

        Why: It keeps your PhysicsManager, Renderer, and AssetManager decoupled. If a chunk of voxels finishes loading, the AssetManager emits an event; the Renderer listens and updates the GPU buffer automatically.

    Command/Task Manager (Job System): Since you are building a voxel engine, you will eventually face frame drops when generating/loading chunks. A TaskManager allows you to offload heavy calculations (procedural generation, file I/O) to worker threads without stalling your main loop.

    Configuration/Settings Manager: Your AppSettings struct is currently static. You need a manager that handles real-time changes to these settings (e.g., changing VSync or resolution mid-game) and notifies the Window and Renderer to re-initialize or adjust their state accordingly.

2. Architectural Refactoring Tips

Looking at your private members, you are heading toward a "God Class" problem. To keep it reactive, consider these changes:
A. Centralized System Registry

Instead of specific unique_ptr members, use a map or a base class list.
C++

// Instead of individual pointers:
std::unordered_map<std::type_index, std::shared_ptr<void>> m_Systems;

template<typename T>
void RegisterSystem(std::shared_ptr<T> system);

template<typename T>
T& GetSystem();

This allows you to add/remove systems dynamically without changing the Application header every time you add a new manager.
B. The "Reactive" Update Pattern

Currently, you have OnUpdate(float dt). A more reactive way to handle your managers is to give them a lifecycle:
C++

class ISystem {
public:
    virtual void OnEvent(Event& e) = 0; // The "reactive" part
    virtual void OnUpdate(float dt) = 0;
};

Now, in your Application::Run() loop, you just iterate through a std::vector<ISystem*> and call Update() on all of them.
C. Avoid std::unique_ptr<void>

In your code, you have std::vector<std::unique_ptr<void>> m_EngineObjects;. Avoid this. You cannot delete a void pointer safely in C++ because the destructor won't be called for the underlying type. Use a base class like IEngineSystem with a virtual destructor instead.
3. Immediate "Voxel-Specific" Managers

Since you are doing voxels, you will likely need:

    Chunk Manager: Handles the lifecycle of voxel chunksвЂ”loading, unloading, and keeping them in memory.

    Voxel Interaction Manager: Handles things like raycasting against the voxel grid to select/place blocks. This bridges the gap between your InputManager and your game logic.

Summary Checklist for your Application.hpp

    Event Bus: Create this first. It allows your AssetManager to talk to your Renderer without them being linked.

    Interface Base Class: Create an ISystem class that has OnUpdate, OnRender, and OnEvent virtual methods.

    Refactor to a System Container: Stop hard-coding every manager as a std::unique_ptr member.

Does your current AssetManager already support asynchronous loading, or is it purely synchronous? Knowing this will help determine how you should build your Task/Job system.